{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609305"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:45:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:45:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16100"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16100"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.32,0.32,0.04,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8791"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74148"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8791"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16100"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59639"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1652"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7662"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20987"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20988"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74148","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74148"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA pathologist is examining tissue from a woman who developed vaginal bleeding three months after a normal pregnancy. The specimen was obtained from a uterine curettage.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following histological features best characterises gestational choriocarcinoma?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Proliferation of mononuclear cytotrophoblasts in sheets","Presence of intact chorionic villi with trophoblast proliferation","Mixture of cytotrophoblast and syncytiotrophoblast without chorionic villi","Hydropic degeneration of villi with trophoblastic overgrowth","Proliferation of multinucleated syncytiotrophoblasts in sheets"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe characteristic histological feature of gestational choriocarcinoma is a \u003Cstrong\u003Emixture of cytotrophoblast and syncytiotrophoblast without chorionic villi\u003C/strong\u003E. The tumour shows a biphasic pattern with sheets of mononuclear cytotrophoblasts surrounded by multinucleated syncytiotrophoblasts, often with extensive haemorrhage and necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProliferation of mononuclear cytotrophoblasts in sheets\u003C/strong\u003E - Choriocarcinoma requires both cell types\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPresence of intact chorionic villi with trophoblast proliferation\u003C/strong\u003E - The absence of villi is a key diagnostic feature\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydropic degeneration of villi with trophoblastic overgrowth\u003C/strong\u003E - This is characteristic of hydatidiform mole, not choriocarcinoma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProliferation of multinucleated syncytiotrophoblasts in sheets\u003C/strong\u003E - The tumour shows both cell types in a disordered arrangement\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis histological appearance reflects the malignant transformation of both trophoblastic cell types that normally form the placenta. The absence of chorionic villi distinguishes choriocarcinoma from other gestational trophoblastic diseases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Gestational choriocarcinoma shows characteristic histological features of both syncytiotrophoblasts and cytotrophoblasts without chorionic villi.","Gestational choriocarcinoma is a highly malignant tumour arising from placental trophoblastic tissue.","The absence of chorionic villi distinguishes choriocarcinoma from other gestational trophoblastic diseases."],"references":["Duffy L, Zhang L, Sheath K, Love DR, George AM. The Diagnosis of Choriocarcinoma in Molar Pregnancies: A Revised Approach in Clinical Testing. J Clin Med Res. 2015 Dec;7(12):961-6. doi: 10.14740/jocmr2236w. Epub 2015 Oct 23. PMID: 26566410; PMCID: PMC4625817","Ghassemzadeh S, Farci F, Kang M. Hydatidiform Mole. [Updated 2023 May 22]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459155/","Singh S, Sardhana M, Sharma S, Chitralkar P. Choriocarcinoma presenting as an isolated bone marrow metastasis-a case report. Ecancermedicalscience. 2014 Jan 29;8:393. doi: 10.3332/ecancer.2014.393. PMID: 24605133; PMCID: PMC3907403","Singh S, Sardhana M, Sharma S, Chitralkar P. Choriocarcinoma presenting as an isolated bone marrow metastasis-a case report. Ecancermedicalscience. 2014 Jan 29;8:393. doi: 10.3332/ecancer.2014.393. PMID: 24605133; PMCID: PMC3907403"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59639"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16100"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59639"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T21:39:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T21:40:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8791"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74148"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/